    {
      "name": "switchInventory",
      "display": "Switch Inventory",
      "datasource_id": 11,
      "dataset_uuid": "362e741d-7040-4456-906b-7ab1b7c97a44",
      "metrics": [
        "Switch Count",
        "Total Switches",
        "Online",
        "Offline",
        "Always Online",
        "Ever Offline",
        "Offline Duration",
        "CPU (%)",
        "Memory (%)",
        "CPU Utilization (%)",
        "Memory Utilization (%)",
        "Free memory",
        "Total memory",
        "PoE Usage (mW)",
        "PoE Free (mW)",
        "PoE Total (mW)",
        "PoE Utilization (%)",
        "Total Attempted Count",
        "Total Allowed Count",
        "Total Dhcp Clients Attempted",
        "Total Dhcp Clients Succeeded",
        "Actual Temperature",
        "Warning Temperature",
        "Shutdown Temperature",
        "IPv4 Unicast Utilization (%)",
        "IPv6 Unicast Utilization (%)",
        "IPv4 Multicast Utilization (%)",
        "IPv6 Multicast Utilization (%)",
        "ARP Utilization (%)",
        "MAC Utilization (%)"
      ],
      "dims": [
        "tag",
        "tagList",
        "switchGroupLevelOneName",
        "switchId",
        "switchName",
        "switchSerial",
        "switchModel",
        "switchStatus",
        "switchFirmware",
        "upTime",
        "numOfPorts",
        "numOfSwitchUnits",
        "routerId",
        "switchIp",
        "isStack"
      ],
      "notes": "Switch health. switchName = friendly name; switchGroupLevelOneName = Venue; Switch MAC shows as switchId. SCALE QUIRK — UNIFORM x100 DOUBLE-SCALE, applies to EVERY utilization metric here: each one is 'SUM(rawCol)/SUM(debug_count)', a plain mean with NO unit conversion, and the raw column already stores the TRUE PERCENTAGE as a magnitude (raw 5.28 means 5.28% utilized). The built-in '%' format then multiplies by 100 AGAIN, so it renders 528%. Affects 'CPU Utilization (%)', 'Memory Utilization (%)', 'MAC Utilization (%)', 'ARP Utilization (%)', 'IPv4 Unicast Utilization (%)', 'IPv6 Unicast Utilization (%)', 'IPv4 Multicast Utilization (%)', 'IPv6 Multicast Utilization (%)'. Verified against a live switch: with default forwarding profile 1 (mac=16384, ip-route=97280, ip6-route=8192 entries), a switch holding 124 MACs stores raw 0.76 = 0.76% (not 0.0076); raw 0.375 IPv4 Unicast and 0.909 IPv6 Unicast back out to ~365 and ~74 routes, which is realistic, whereas reading them as fractions would demand 36,480 and 7,447 routes, which the tables and the box cannot hold. Do NOT read the small raw values as 0-1 fractions — that misreading is easy to make because on a lightly loaded switch a double-scaled value still lands under 100% and looks plausible; only MAC ran high enough (528%) to be obviously broken. 'PoE Utilization (%)' is not yet CLI-verified; treat it the same until someone checks it against real power draw. To render correctly, use custom SQL like '1.0 * SUM(macUtilization) / SUM(debug_count) / 100.0' with .1% format (renders 0.8%), or show the raw number under a (%) header with a plain .2f format (renders 0.76). The scaling is baked into the ingested raw columns, not the metric SQL.",
      "raw_columns": {
        "MAC Utilization (%)": "macUtilization",
        "ARP Utilization (%)": "arpUtilization",
        "IPv4 Unicast Utilization (%)": "ipv4UnicastUtilization",
        "IPv6 Unicast Utilization (%)": "ipv6UnicastUtilization",
        "IPv4 Multicast Utilization (%)": "ipv4MulticastUtilization",
        "IPv6 Multicast Utilization (%)": "ipv6MulticastUtilization"
      },
